<TITLE>Da Gama Hints At Interest In Bafana Job</TITLE>
<TEXT>
Bafana Bafana assistant coach Owen Da Gama believes that for any coach it would be an honour to coach the national team Following Shakes Mashaba s dismissal at the end of last year the South African national team is currently coachless with Roger Da Sa Milutin Sredojevic Gavin Hunt Muhsin Ertugral Carlos Queiroz Herv Renard and Pitso Mosimane rumoured to be shortlisted for the role When asked about how a new coach could change the dynamics of the team Da Gama said that it will depend on circumstances before saying that he is also considering the next step for his own future It all depends on who the person is coming in and what the situation is And obviously for myself as well I m a very experienced coach I ve gone over 54 matches with Bafana and over 30 matches with the under 23s he told Soccer Laduma That s a lot of matches at national level and for me I can t just be a journeyman I can t just be an assistant coach all the time So I ve got to weigh up my options see what the bosses say and then just take it from there Benni I Want To Transform Players Into Stars Da Gama was then asked directly whether he d be interested in taking over the hotseat to which he replied by providing reasons why he s suited to the role It would be an honour to be Bafana coach one day I think any coach in South Africa would be interested he continued There s that natural progression so why not I ve got the experience and I ve coach at the highest level in the PSL I ve played at the highest level in Europe and we ve got immediate knowledge of the team so why not I ve got a lot of confidence in myself and my ability but I will wait for my bosses at SAFA however to give me directions 
